excerpt: This former estate is now a 144-acre park with diverse garden areas, grassy expanses & a greenhouse.
detail_description: Shinjuku Gyoen National Garden, a former estate turned 144-acre park, was originally created as a recreational garden for the Imperial family. It is an Important Cultural Property and features three types of gardens: English, French, and Japanese. Throughout the year, the park hosts various events such as photography lessons, chrysanthemum flower exhibitions, and traditional Japanese art performances.
name: Shinjuku Gyoen National Garden
address: 11 Naitomachi, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0014, Japan

excerpt: Kenzo Tange-designed City Hall complex with views from the tallest building's observation decks.
detail_description: The Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building, a stunning architectural marvel designed by Kenzo Tange, is a must-visit destination for anyone exploring the vibrant city of Tokyo. This iconic complex features two impressive towers, each offering free observatories on their 45th floors that provide breathtaking panoramic views of Shinjuku's skyline and beyond. Recently, the buildings have gained even more attention due to the TOKYO Night & Light event, showcasing the world's largest permanent projection mapping display on their exterior.
name: Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building
address: 2 Chome-8-1 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 163-8001, Japan

excerpt: Festive, popular city district famed for its narrow, winding alleys & numerous snug taverns.
detail_description: Shinjuku Golden Gai is a lively and popular district in Tokyo, known for its narrow and winding alleys filled with cozy taverns. This hidden gem offers a nostalgic atmosphere, reminiscent of Japan's post-war era, where small bars that can only accommodate a few patrons at a time provide an intimate setting for drinks with friends. While the area has gained popularity among international visitors, it still retains its local charm and may have some establishments with 'Locals Only' signs.
name: Shinjuku Golden-Gai
address: Kabukicho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0021, Japan

excerpt: Compact Edo-period Shinto shrine known for its serene atmosphere & yearly festivals.
detail_description: Hanazono Shrine, located in the heart of Shinjuku, is a compact Edo-period Shinto shrine dedicated to Inari Okami, the god of trade and business success. The grounds feature smaller shrines devoted to various deities, including a kitsune fox shrine with a tunnel of torii gates and the Geino Asama Shrine for performers.
name: Hanazono Shrine
address: 5 Chome-17-3 Shinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0022, Japan

excerpt: Landmark alleyway featuring a selection of food stalls for simple fare & alcoholic drinks.
detail_description: Omoide Yokocho, also known as Memory Lane Alley or Yakitori Alley, is a renowned landmark in Tokyo located just north of Shinjuku station. Once a black market area post-World War II, it has transformed into a bustling alleyway filled with tightly compressed restaurants offering cheap izakaya food and alcoholic drinks. The vibrant atmosphere attracts both locals and tourists seeking to savor its culinary offerings.
name: Omoide Yokocho Memory Lane
address: 1 Chome-2 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0023, Japan

excerpt: Famed entertainment district best known for adult-oriented nightlife plus clubs, pubs & snack bars.
detail_description: Kabukicho, also known as the Sleepless Town, is a renowned entertainment district in Japan, particularly famous for its adult-oriented nightlife. This bustling pedestrian area in Shinjuku is adorned with neon signs and offers a vibrant atmosphere filled with cinemas, shops like the 24-hour Don Quijote superstore, karaoke bars such as Studio Himawari, and various restaurants. Additionally, it's home to massage parlors, nightclubs, and love hotels.
name: Kabukicho
address: Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0021, Japan

excerpt: Samurai museum featuring costumes that can be worn by visitors, regular sword battles & more.
detail_description: The Samurai Museum in Shinjuku offers a captivating journey into the world of samurai, showcasing an extensive collection of armor, weapons, and art spanning 700 years. Visitors can witness live demonstrations with weapons and even participate in workshops. The museum also features a shop where unique souvenirs and samurai-related items can be purchased, including antique katana and other swords as well as armor with free international shipping available.
name: Samurai Museum
address: Japan, 〒160-0021 Tokyo, Shinjuku City, Kabukicho, 2 Chome−25−6 ホライズン・ビルディング, 1F・2F

detail_description: Shinjuku Station is located in the entertainment district of Shinjuku, known for its vibrant atmosphere and diverse attractions. While it was once labeled as a red light district due to its history, today it offers a variety of experiences including movie theaters, live music venues, and unique stores. The station itself is an attraction with millions of people passing through daily, making it an ideal spot for photography enthusiasts seeking interesting perspectives.
name: Shinjuku Station
address: 3 Chome-38-1 Shinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0022, Japan

detail_description: The Robot Restaurant in Tokyo is a must-see attraction that offers an otherworldly experience. From the vibrant neon colors bouncing off mirrors to the eclectic mix of old traditions and futuristic trends, this restaurant provides an incredible and unique show that lasts about 90 minutes. It's a family-friendly venue with a lively atmosphere, making it one of the best activities in Tokyo to share with friends. While some may have mixed reviews, experiencing it firsthand is recommended for those seeking an unforgettable and entertaining evening.
name: Robot restaurant
address: B1F, 1 Chome-7-7 Kabukicho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0021, Japan

detail_description: Located in Kabuki-cho, Shinjuku, the Godzilla Head is a 12-meter tall life-sized model of the iconic character. Situated on the outdoor terrace of the eighth floor of Hotel Gracery in the Toho Building, this monstrous head is a popular attraction. Visitors can admire its piercing eyes and sharp teeth from 130 feet below or take an elevator to get a closer look.
name: Godzilla Head
address: 1 Chome-19 Kabukicho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0021, Japan

excerpt: Leafy park with paths, a playground & a small pool during the summer, plus space for sports.
detail_description: Shinjuku Chuo Park is a verdant oasis in the heart of Tokyo, offering a serene escape with its lush greenery, walking paths, and recreational facilities. The park features a playground and a small pool that provides relief during the summer months. Visitors can also enjoy various sports activities within the park's expansive grounds. Surrounded by notable attractions, the park is situated near the Metropolitan Government Building and Shinjuku Gyoen National Garden.
name: Shinjuku Chuo Park
address: 2 Chome-11 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0023, Japan

excerpt: Started as a kimono store in 1886, this famous destination is now known for high fashion shopping.
detail_description: Isetan Shinjuku is a renowned department store in Japan, tracing its origins back to 1886 when it started as a kimono shop. Today, it is celebrated for its diverse range of products, from luxury brands to casual wear. The flagship store in Shinjuku is considered the birthplace of fashion trends and offers an extensive selection of fashion items from top global brands, beauty products, and gourmet food.
name: Isetan Shinjuku
address: 3 Chome-14-1 Shinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0022, Japan

excerpt: Public observation room at the top of the Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building with gift shops.
detail_description: The Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building North Observatory is a must-visit for tourists, offering stunning views of the city. Located at 202 meters above ground, this free public observation room provides an opportunity to admire the megalopolis that is Tokyo. While both the South and North Observation Decks offer beautiful views, the North tower is recommended for its extended hours and perfect night-time vistas. Visitors can also enjoy a lounge area and may even catch a glimpse of Mount Fuji on clear days.
name: Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building North Observation Deck
address: 東京都庁第一本庁舎 45F, 2 Chome-8-1 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 163-8001, Japan

excerpt: Cobbled-street neighborhood lined with fashionable shopping, cafes & French dining.
detail_description: Kagurazaka is a charming neighborhood in Tokyo, known for its cobbled streets, fashionable shopping, and diverse dining options. As you wander uphill from the main street, you'll discover a blend of nostalgic establishments from Edo Japan and modern European-influenced eateries. This trendy area was once a lively geisha district, and remnants of its heritage can still be seen in traditional ryotei restaurants and kimono stores alongside Michelin-starred establishments and galleries.
name: Kagurazaka
address: Shinjuku City, Tokyo 162-0825, Japan

excerpt: Small museum featuring paintings by notable Japanese & European artists, plus a cafe.
detail_description: Nestled on the 42nd floor of a stunning skyscraper, SOMPO Museum of Art showcases an impressive collection of paintings by renowned Japanese and European artists. Originally known as the Seiji Togo Memorial Museum, it was renamed when it moved to its current location in Shinjuku. The museum is home to about 630 works, including pieces by Van Gogh and Seiji Togo.
name: SOMPO Museum of Art
address: 1 Chome-26-1 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0023, Japan

excerpt: Complex with multilevel retail towers set around a terrace known for seasonal lighting events.
detail_description: Shinjuku Southern Terrace is a multi-level retail complex with a terrace that hosts seasonal lighting events. It's located across from the south exit of Shinjuku Station and features a variety of restaurants and shops, including well-known brands like Starbucks, Krispy Kreme, and Eddie Bauer. The area is elegantly styled with trees and is perfect for leisurely strolls or enjoying a coffee break. During winter, the terrace dazzles visitors with beautiful illuminations.
name: Shinjuku Southern Terrace
address: 2 Chome-2-1 Yoyogi, Shibuya, Tokyo 151-8583, Japan

excerpt: Annual exhibitions, lectures & events explore the life & work of a beloved avant-garde artist.
detail_description: The YAYOI KUSAMA Museum, located in a suburban area of Shinjuku, is a five-story building entirely devoted to the avant-garde artist's works. It features an array of larger-than-life pieces, from her famous infinity room series to polka-dotted paintings and sculptures. The museum changes its exhibitions twice a year, offering visitors the chance to experience different aspects of Kusama's prolific work.
name: YAYOI KUSAMA Museum
address: 107 Bentencho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 162-0851, Japan

excerpt: Reminiscent of the Eiffel Tower, this landmark features observation areas & other attractions.
detail_description: Tokyo Tower, reminiscent of the Eiffel Tower, is a significant landmark in Tokyo and Japan. It was opened in 1958 and celebrated its 60th anniversary in 2018. Standing at 333m tall, it offers observation areas at 150m and 250m high, providing stunning views of Mt. Fuji, Mt. Tsukuba, and the entire Tokyo metropolis.
name: Tokyo Tower
address: 4 Chome-2-8 Shibakoen, Minato City, Tokyo 105-0011, Japan

excerpt: Firefighting museum with kid-friendly exhibits, fire gear & equipment, plus trucks & helicopters.
detail_description: The Fire Museum, operated by the Tokyo Fire Department, offers a captivating journey through Japan's firefighting and disaster prevention history. Located at 3-10 Yotsuya, Shinjuku-ku, Tokyo, the museum houses over 8,000 reference materials and authentic artifacts from different historical periods. Visitors can explore traditional and modern exhibits while kids can enjoy dressing up as firefighters, exploring vintage fire trucks in the basement, and participating in hands-on activities on the third floor.
name: Fire Museum
address: 3 Chome-１０-10 Yotsuya, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0004, Japan

excerpt: Well-known park with an indoor ice skating rink, driving range, baseball diamonds & tennis courts.
detail_description: Meiji Jingu Gaien, located in the Aoyama area of Tokyo, is a large park that offers various recreational activities such as an indoor ice skating rink, driving range, baseball diamonds, and tennis courts. Despite being less talked about compared to its famous neighboring parks like Yoyogi Park and Shinjuku Park, Meiji Jingu Gaien's beautiful paths and iconic avenue lined with Ginkgo trees make it a worthwhile destination for visitors.
name: Meiji Jingu Gaien
address: 1-1 Kasumigaokamachi, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0013, Japan

excerpt: Ōkubo, also known as Shin-Ōkubo, is a neighborhood in Shinjuku, Tokyo, Japan. The neighborhood is built around Shin-Ōkubo Station, accessible on the Yamanote Line. It is known for its extensive Korean community, and is often called Tokyo Koreatown. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Okubo, also known as Shin-Okubo, is a vibrant neighborhood in Tokyo, Japan, centered around the Shin-Okubo Station on the Yamanote Line. It's renowned for its large Korean community and is often referred to as Tokyo Koreatown. The area offers a multicultural experience with Korean shops, restaurants, and cultural events. Food enthusiasts will delight in the diverse range of authentic Korean cuisine available here, from barbecue to sweet treats, as well as Japanese and international foods.
name: Okubo
address: Shinjuku City, Tokyo 169-0072, Japan

detail_description: Shin-Okubo Korean Town is a hidden gem in Japan, offering authentic homemade Korean dishes like the fragrant salt-grilled aigamo served on a sizzling iron plate. Visitors can also explore various Korean cosmetics stores to enhance their beauty from both inside and out. The area provides an opportunity to experience different aspects of Korean culture while in Japan, making it a lively and enjoyable destination for food, drinks, and shopping.
name: Shin-Okubo Korea Town
address: 1 Chome-4-15 Hyakunincho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 169-0073, Japan

excerpt: Posh rooms & suites, some with Mount Fuji views, in a ritzy hotel offering an indoor pool & a spa.
detail_description: Nestled in the upscale area of west Shinjuku, Park Hyatt Tokyo offers luxurious rooms and suites, some featuring breathtaking views of Mount Fuji. The hotel provides a serene retreat from the bustling city, with a complimentary shuttle to Shinjuku Station. Made famous by its appearance in Lost in Translation, this five-star hotel boasts elegant rooms with stunning vistas of the city lights and walk-in closets.
name: Park Hyatt Tokyo
address: 2, 3 Chome-7-1 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 163-1055, Japan

excerpt: Tranquil, tree-filled religious complex, with 12 small shrines dedicated to 12 different deities.
detail_description: Nestled in the bustling district of Nishi-shinjuku, Shinjuku Juniso Kumano-jinja Shrine is a serene religious complex featuring 12 small shrines dedicated to different deities. Originally enshrining the main deities from the historical province of Kishu, it now hosts a local deity of Shinjuku. The shrine's modern reconstruction after World War II still preserves its cultural significance and traditional Japanese design.
name: Shinjuku Juniso Kumano-jinja Shrine
address: 2 Chome-11-2 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0023, Japan

detail_description: NEWoMan Shinjuku is a trendy shopping complex that has become a favorite among locals for its unpretentious size and stylish design. It opened in 2016 and features around 100 retailers offering a wide range of products, from fashion to cosmetics and miscellaneous goods. The facility spans over 6 floors, including a rooftop garden terrace on the 6th floor with stunning views of Shinjuku station at sunset.
name: NEWoMan Shinjuku
address: 4 Chome-1-6 Shinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0022, Japan

excerpt: Playful, interactive amusement center with ninja-themed activities like star throwing & sword play.
detail_description: Ninja Trick House in Tokyo offers a playful and interactive experience with ninja-themed activities such as star throwing and sword play. Located just a 3-minute walk from bustling Kabukicho in the heart of Shinjuku, this black 4-story building is a must-visit for those seeking an immersive cultural experience. The house was created by a ninja-loving owner to showcase the allure of ninjas.
name: Ninja Trick House In Tokyo
address: 第一和幸ビル 4階, 2 Chome-28-13 Kabukicho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0021, Japan

detail_description: Shibuya Scramble Crossing, located outside Shibuya station in Tokyo, is a must-see experience for visitors. It's the world's busiest pedestrian crossing, with over one million people crossing it daily. The surrounding shopping centers offer various lookout points to observe the madness below, and the new Shibuya Sky outdoor viewing deck provides a stunning view from 229 meters above street level. For great photos, shooting from above at night captures the neon lights and bustling activity.
name: Shibuya Scramble Crossing
address: Shibuya, Tokyo, Japan

detail_description: Tokyu Kabukicho Tower, a newly opened 225-meter high-rise complex in Shinjuku's Kabukicho area, is a vibrant hub of entertainment and leisure. With 48 floors above ground and 5 below, it features a diverse range of attractions including a live music hall, movie theaters, theaters, and an array of dining options. The space also houses ZEROTOKYO - an evening entertainment venue within Zepp Shinjuku.
name: Tokyu Kabukicho Tower
address: 1 Chome-29-1 Kabukicho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0021, Japan

excerpt: Popular, immersive museum known for its colorful, futuristic digital art installations & photo ops.
detail_description: teamLab Borderless: MORI Building DIGITAL ART MUSEUM is a popular and immersive museum featuring colorful, futuristic digital art installations that offer great photo opportunities. Since its opening in 2018, it has become the world's most visited museum dedicated to a single artist/group. The museum will be closing this year due to redevelopment of the building housing it, but not before hosting its last cherry blossom-themed exhibition.
name: teamLab Borderless: MORI Building DIGITAL ART MUSEUM
address: Azabudai Hills Garden Plaza B, B1, 5 Chome-９ Toranomon, Minato City, Tokyo 106-0041, Japan

excerpt: Public park with a pond, laid out in the Edo-period style, on the site of 17th-century Shogun villa.
detail_description: Hamarikyu Gardens is a public park located on the site of a 17th-century Shogun villa, featuring an Edo-period style layout with a pond. Situated along the Sumida River, visitors can enjoy views of Tokyo Skytree from nearby Sumida Park and take a short walk or cruise to Hamarikyu Garden and Odaiba Island. This garden was meticulously designed over time by successive shoguns, drawing seawater from Tokyo Bay.
name: Hamarikyu Gardens
address: 1-1 Hamarikyuteien, Chuo City, Tokyo 104-0046, Japan

excerpt: One of the city’s top shopping districts, Ginza is packed with upmarket boutiques and ritzy cocktail and sushi bars. Fine jewelry is sold in the 1930s Wako Honkan department store, while ultramodern Ginza Place specializes in high-tech electronics. On weekends, main drag Chuo Dori becomes a stylish pedestrian promenade. Traditional Japanese dance and drama is staged at the landmark Kabuki-za theater.
detail_description: Ginza is a renowned luxurious shopping district, featuring high-end boutiques, upscale cocktail and sushi bars, and prestigious department stores. The area's rich history as a commercial center is evident in its blend of historic shops and cutting-edge fashion outlets. On weekends, the main street becomes a stylish pedestrian promenade, offering traditional Japanese performances at the landmark Kabuki-za theater.
name: Ginza
address: Chuo City, Tokyo 104-0061, Japan

excerpt: Opened in 2008 in a former elementary school, this museum houses toys & games from around the world.
detail_description: The Tokyo Toy Museum, located in a former elementary school building, offers a diverse collection of toys and games from around the globe. The museum features three floors and an outdoor playground for sunny days. Children up to two years old can explore the first floor with wooden toys and structures, while older kids can enjoy the Wood Toy Forest on the second floor. Visitors of all ages can engage in workshops to create their own toys.
name: Tokyo Toy Museum
address: Japan, 〒160-0004 Tokyo, Shinjuku City, Yotsuya, 4 Chome−20, 四谷ひろば内

excerpt: Compact, 16th-century shrine dedicated to one of the Seven Lucky Gods, with stone tiger statues.
detail_description: Zenkoku-ji Temple, a 16th-century Buddhist shrine located in the Kagurazaka neighborhood of Shinjuku City, is a modest yet charming landmark with a rich history. The temple, dedicated to Bishamonten and featuring a 30-meter wooden statue of the deity, was first built in 1595 under the orders of Tokugawa Ieyasu.
name: Zenkoku-ji Temple
address: 5 Chome-３６ Kagurazaka, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 162-0825, Japan

excerpt: Art including a Robert Indiana "LOVE" sculpture & works by Roy Lichtenstein surround this tower.
detail_description: Shinjuku i-LAND Tower is a 44-story skyscraper located in the Nishi-Shinjuku district, surrounded by urban functionality such as offices, shops, residential areas, and schools. The area features public artworks with a theme of human love and the future, including the iconic LOVE sculpture at the front entrance. The building houses offices but has an interesting circular courtyard at its base with shops and restaurants. Visitors can enjoy contemporary art scattered throughout the area.
name: Shinjuku i-LAND Tower
address: 6 Chome-5-1 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 163-1390, Japan

detail_description: Takashimaya is a renowned department store located in various cities in Japan, such as Shinjuku and Yokohama. In Shinjuku, the Takashimaya Times Square houses a fantastic kids floor on the 9th level, offering amenities like a baby rest area, toy stores, a kids hair salon, and a mom-and-kids-friendly cafe. The store also features high-end brands alongside popular and affordable ones like Disney and Kinokuniya Books.
name: Takashimaya
address: 5 Chome-24-2 Sendagaya, Shibuya, Tokyo 151-8580, Japan

excerpt: Bustling locality features the world's busiest train station, Tokyo's largest park, pubs & cafes.
detail_description: Shinjuku, a vibrant district in Tokyo, is renowned for its dazzling skyline adorned with neon-lit skyscrapers. This western area offers an array of entertainment, dining, and shopping options, attracting both locals and visitors. The bustling Shinjuku Station serves as Japan's busiest transit hub, providing access to various train lines. Additionally, the district boasts luxurious hotels with stunning views of the cityscape and Mount Fuji.
name: Shinjuku
address: Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0022, Japan

excerpt: Tokyo business district known for its sleek skyscrapers & Shinjuku Central Park.
detail_description: Nishishinjuku, a bustling Tokyo business district, is characterized by its modern skyscrapers and the scenic Shinjuku Central Park. The area offers a diverse culinary scene, ranging from budget-friendly eateries to high-rise restaurants with stunning city views. To the north of the station lies Memory Lane Alley, also known as Omoide Yokocho, where cozy izakaya joints serve affordable local fare to post-work crowds.
name: Nishishinjuku
address: Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0023, Japan

excerpt: Spa featuring soaking pools with water from natural hot springs, plus massages, saunas & lounges.
detail_description: Thermae-Yu is a modern onsen located in Shinjuku Kabukicho, offering a convenient and rejuvenating experience amid the city surroundings. The facility features soaking pools with water from natural hot springs, stone saunas, and various relaxation areas. What sets Thermae-Yu apart is its extended hours, language support, and a range of amenities including a beauty salon, scrub treatments, and dining options.
name: Thermae-Yu
address: テルマー湯内 B1F, 1 Chome-1-2 Kabukicho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0021, Japan

excerpt: Convenience store selling groceries, toys, footwear & other household items.
detail_description: Don Quijote is a popular discount store franchise in Japan, with multiple outlets in the Shinjuku area. The store offers a wide range of products at discounted prices, including groceries, toys, footwear, electronics, cosmetics, snacks, clothing and household items. It operates 24 hours a day, making it convenient for visitors to enjoy late-night shopping after experiencing the nightlife in Shinjuku. The store spans six stories and provides a vibrant atmosphere with an overwhelming array of products.
name: Don Quijote
address: 5 Chome-68-5 Nakano, Nakano City, Tokyo 164-0001, Japan

detail_description: Matsumoto Kiyoshi is a prominent drugstore chain in Shinjuku, with nine stores spread across the district. The stores are conveniently located in various areas, making it easy for visitors to shop. Operating hours typically run from 10 AM to 9 PM, with some offering extended hours for added convenience. This one-stop-shop is renowned for its wide range of cosmetic products and local beauty items, particularly makeup and skincare essentials.
name: Matsumoto Kiyoshi
address: 3 Chome-17-3 Shinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0022, Japan

excerpt: Surrounded by forest, this venerable Shinto shrine features a seasonal iris garden.
detail_description: Nestled within a lush forest, Meiji Jingu is a serene Shinto shrine dedicated to Emperor Meiji and Empress Shoken. Established in 1920 and reconstructed after World War II, this tranquil haven features over 100,000 trees donated from across Japan. Each year during Golden Week in late April, the shrine comes alive with its vibrant spring festival that showcases traditional performances like Bugaku dance and Noh theater.
name: Meiji Jingu
address: 1-1 Yoyogikamizonocho, Shibuya, Tokyo 151-8557, Japan

excerpt: Tranquil, scenic landscape garden dating to the 17th century, with walking paths, a pond & bridges.
detail_description: Koishikawa Korakuen Garden is a serene and picturesque landscape garden that dates back to the 17th century. It features walking paths, a pond, and bridges, creating a tranquil atmosphere for visitors. The garden was constructed during the Edo Period by Yorifusa Tokugawa and completed by Mitsukuni. Its design includes elements evoking Chinese scenery and famous locations throughout Japan.
name: Koishikawa Korakuen Garden
address: 1 Chome-6-6 Koraku, Bunkyo City, Tokyo 112-0004, Japan

excerpt: This site with scenic gardens & tours of the grounds is the main residence of the emperor of Japan.
detail_description: The Imperial Palace in Tokyo is the main residence of the emperor of Japan and has been home to a succession of emperors since 1868. The scenic East Gardens are open to the public throughout the year, offering a popular spot for enjoying cherry blossoms. While Marunouchi is known as a business district, it also offers attractions such as skyscrapers, department stores, and architectural wonders like the Shin-Marunouchi Building and Tokyo International Forum.
name: Imperial Palace
address: 1-1 Chiyoda, Chiyoda City, Tokyo 100-8111, Japan

excerpt: Stately museum complex devoted to the art & antiquities of Japan, as well as other Asian countries.
detail_description: The Tokyo National Museum, also known as Kahaku, is a grand museum complex that showcases the art and antiquities of Japan and other Asian countries. Celebrating its 140th anniversary, the museum offers a comprehensive exploration of Japan's nature and science through permanent exhibitions featuring prehistoric flora and fauna, historical voyages of the Japanese people, and a unique spherical 3D movie theater experience.
name: Tokyo National Museum
address: 13-9 Uenokoen, Taito City, Tokyo 110-8712, Japan

excerpt: Large, modern venue presenting temporary exhibitions of Japanese & international art.
detail_description: The National Art Center Tokyo is a large, modern venue in Roppongi that showcases temporary exhibitions of both Japanese and international art. The building's unique facade contrasts with the surrounding architecture, embodying Kisho Kurokawa's architectural concepts of natural materials and adaptability to surroundings. With its wavy glass exterior, the museum spans 14,000 square meters and hosts works from renowned artists without maintaining a permanent collection.
name: The National Art Center, Tokyo
address: 7 Chome-22-2 Roppongi, Minato City, Tokyo 106-8558, Japan

detail_description: Meiji Jingu Baseball Stadium, located just a short distance from Shibuya, offers an exciting opportunity to experience a real baseball game in a massive 30,000-seat venue. As the home ground of the Yakult Swallows and a historic site for baseball in Tokyo, it's a must-visit for sports enthusiasts. The stadium provides an entertaining experience even for those unfamiliar with the sport. Visitors can enjoy delicious food at reasonable prices while taking in the game.
name: Meiji Jingu Baseball Stadium
address: 3-1 Kasumigaokamachi, Shinjuku City, Tokyo, Japan

excerpt: Spacious, leafy complex with traditional shrines as well as modern architecture.
detail_description: Nestled in a leafy complex just behind Kagurazaka Station, Akagi Shrine is a blend of traditional and modern architecture. Established in 1300, it enshrines Iwatsutsuo-no-mikoto and Akagihime-no-mikoto, known for warding off evil and granting women's wishes.
name: Akagi Shrine
address: 1-10 Akagi Motomachi, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 162-0817, Japan

excerpt: Modern office building with a triangular design, a central atrium & visible exterior cargo elevator.
detail_description: The Shinjuku Sumitomo Building is a striking modern office building located in the bustling Shinjuku business district of Tokyo. Completed in 1974, it was one of the first skyscrapers in the area and briefly held the title of Japan's tallest building. Its distinctive triangular design and visible exterior cargo elevator make it a notable feature of the city skyline.
name: Shinjuku Sumitomo Building
address: 2 Chome-6-1 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0023, Japan

excerpt: Rebuilt 1,000-year-old Shinto site with crimson torii gates, fishponds & horseback archer statues.
detail_description: Ana-hachimangu Shrine, located in Tokyo's Shinjuku district, is a reconstructed 1,000-year-old Shinto sanctuary featuring traditional Japanese architecture with vibrant vermilion torii gates and serene gardens. The shrine offers a tranquil escape from the city and hosts seasonal festivals and cultural events, providing insight into Japan's spiritual heritage. The majestic shrine is adorned with crimson torii gates, fishponds, and statues of horseback archers.
name: Ana-hachimangu Shrine
address: 2 Chome-1-11 Nishiwaseda, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 162-0051, Japan

name: Tokyo Opera City Recital Hall
address: 3 Chome-20-2 Nishishinjuku, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 163-1490, Japan
